Reasoning: The paper discusses the use of bibliographic coupling networks and indicators to analyze the structural role of core literature in defining intellectual landscapes in the humanities, specifically in the field of history. This involves methods and techniques that are commonly used in digital libraries (cs.DL) and information retrieval (cs.IR). The paper also touches on the role of reference works and primary sources, which are relevant to human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Additionally, the analysis of bibliographic coupling networks and communities can be seen as a form of social network analysis (cs.SI), and the use of natural language processing techniques to analyze the content of scholarly publications is relevant to computational linguistics (cs.CL).
